Aside from implementation details, what is the primary use case for this? Easier chaining?

My concern with this is that this makes `nextTick`'s behavior inconsistent based on the environment. E.g. code that relies on the returned Promise that works in Chrome will break in IE9 if no proper polyfill was provided.
@yyx990803 I can definitely see your point and even IE11 would break without a polyfill. I see this as an advanced usage similar to Vuex, which also relies on Promise support. The need for a polyfill in IE would also be noted prominently whenever mentioning this syntax alternative (I'm personally a fan of including the very light-weight [polyfill.io](https://polyfill.io/v2/docs/) in every project). 

Given that, if you're afraid users might stumble upon the Promise syntax without reading the documentation on `nextTick` or realizing the limits of native Promise support, I would not be at all offended if this PR were rejected. üôÇ 

The primary use case is ergonomics - easier chaining and `async`/`await` usage:

### Promise chaining

``` js
this.fetchTodos()
  .then(this.$nextTick)
  .then(() => {
    // something that relies on the DOM being updated
  })
```

### `async`/`await`

``` js
watch: {
  todos: async () => {
    await this.$nextTick()
    // something that relies on the DOM being updated
  }
}
```

---

With the current implementation of `nextTick`, I also want to acknowledge that these are not actually new possibilities being opened, as `Promise.resolve().then` will work just as well as `Vue.nextTick().then`. However, I would argue that applications should ignore the internal implementation, since it's subject to change - and is especially likely to with other compile targets. That's why the use cases above assume `nextTick` is a magical black box.

