Currently, whenever you call `Vue.set` or `Vue.delete`, all observers on the object being modified are executed.  This is a "safe" practice, because it ensures that any objects who had previously attempted to access the key being added or deleted get their dependencies re-computed.

However, consider the case where you have an object with many different keys and watchers, which might be expensive to call.  In this case, `Vue.set` will do a lot of work executing all of the watchers, even if none of them respond to the new field in the object, causing poor performance.

Here is a fiddle to demonstrate the issue: https://jsfiddle.net/exe3nxzg/2/ .  Adding new keys to the object causes the watcher on the original field to be triggered, even though that watcher doesn't care about the values of the new keys.

This PR offers a possible fix to the problem, which is to add an options object as the final argument of `Vue.set` and `Vue.delete`.  If the user wishes to manually suppress notifications on the object and prevent all watchers from being computed, they can pass `{ notify: false }` as the final argument.

Another possible fix would be to add a new function called `Vue.get`.  If `Vue.set` replaces the syntax `obj[key]=value` and `Vue.delete` replaces the syntax `delete obj[key]`, then `Vue.get` would replace the syntax `obj[key] || default`.  More precisely, a definition could look something like:

```js
Vue.get = function(obj, key, defaultValue) {
	if (!obj.hasOwnProperty(key)) {
		// create the key on the object with the default value.
		// call defineReactive(), etc.
		// however, do NOT call notify on the object.
	}
	return obj[key];
};
```

This way, whenever a key access is attempted, a reactive is left behind, such that setting the property in the future, even via `Vue.set`, will not cause a full notify.

Thoughts?

