@jbrooksuk What is the use case for displaying 0, 1 or more than 2 decimals on a currency?
> @jbrooksuk What is the use case for displaying 0, 1 or more than 2 decimals on a currency?

@posva mainly it's just when you have a more precise number but need to display it differently.
@jbrooksuk I see the concern on arbitrary numbers but what about currencies?
> @jbrooksuk I see the concern on arbitrary numbers but what about currencies?

When you don't want the trailing ".00" on the end. At least in $ and ¬£ you tend to display ¬£99.00 as ¬£99
@posva @jbrooksuk What about instead of an option to specify decimal places, having an option to display whole numbers without decimals? So for example in USD, `22` would become `"$22"`, but `22.2` would become `"$22.20"`. That way, you can guarantee you're not hiding rounding errors or other miscalculations.
Perhaps a boolean such as `preferIntegers`?
@jbrooksuk @posva  I believe your concern is valid for removing trailing '.00'.

For inspiration: Angular provides a similar parameter called _fractionSize_ on their currency filter which you can reference here: https://docs.angularjs.org/api/ng/filter/currency

@chrisvfritz In that case an optional flag to the currency filter such as _no_trailing_zeros_ could be an option.
> @posva @jbrooksuk What about instead of an option to specify decimal places, having an option to display whole numbers without decimals? So for example in USD, 22 would become "$22", but 22.2 would become "$22.20". That way, you can guarantee you're not hiding rounding errors or other miscalculations.

@chrisvfritz that doesn't work in some scenarios. For example, the app I'm building needs to display the whole price, not the pence, but elsewhere it needs the pence.
Remember that this is an optional parameter and the default behaviour continues to be the same. I feel this adds more flexibility.
@jbrooksuk So in some cases there is a non-zero pence in the price, but you still prefer to hide it?
> @jbrooksuk So in some cases there is a non-zero pence in the price, but you still prefer to hide it?

Yeah, and without re-implementing the filter, it's not "impossible". Like I said, this is an _optional_ extension of existing functionality. It's just not strict anymore.
@FadyMak I like the `noTrailingZeroes` name! :smiley: **Edit: Although it just occurred to me, `$22.20` technically has a trailing zero, so that could be confusing.**

@jbrooksuk Hmm, I worry that might be an edge case. I feel like suppressing non-zero pence/cents/etc could very easily (and unintentionally) hide errors in other applications, as people might use it hoping to only suppress trailing zeroes.
> @jbrooksuk Hmm, I worry that might be an edge case. I feel like suppressing non-zero pence/cents/etc could very easily (and unintentionally) hide errors in other applications, as people might use it hoping to only suppress trailing zeroes.

If they do, then that's a matter of not understanding what the filter is doing.
@jbrooksuk I agree, but I think in designing APIs, it's important to be wary of releasing features that are especially _prone_ to misunderstanding. I also have a preference for explicitness though. Since that's a feature that could easily hide rounding/calculation errors, I would want to make sure I (and other team members) remained very aware of that. So I would personally never use such an option even if it existed. I would instead opt for explicitness - with something like a computed value called `priceWithoutPence` that I used the currency filter on instead. And in computing that value, seeing `Math.floor`/`Math.round`/`Math.ceil` would make it more obvious how we were rounding.

What are your thoughts @posva @FadyMak?
@jbrooksuk I agree with the point of being explicit. I believe the core API should provide basic functionality such as specifying the _decimalPlaces_ as an **optional** parameter to the currency filter. This would result in the currency filter rounding to the specified number of decimal places.

Since the number of decimal places varies by locale (i.e.: the US Dollar ($) is usually represented with 2 decimal places whereas the Kuwaiti Dinar (KWD) is represented with 3 decimal places), the **decimalPlaces** parameter would default to the maximum number of decimal places for that specific locale.

Please reference the [ISO 4217 World Currency Format](http://www.thefinancials.com/?SubSectionID=curformat) to see the default number of decimal places a specific currency displays.

If a developer wishes to perform more complex formatting, they can achieve that by defining a custom filter of their own and chaining it to the currency filter. 
Defaulting based on locale could be dangerous?
@FadyMak Good to know about some currencies using 3 decimal places instead of 2 or 0 - thanks for linking to that resource!
I would actually create a precision filter away from this to allow for more use cases,  and chain the filters.  This will help add more to the API at the same time as resolving this issue. 

This filter then should not strip the amount of decimal places. Which will simplify the usage of this filter. 
@jbrooksuk thanks for the PR! So to sum it up:
1. We want to avoid making built-in filters more complex than they are right now, because Vue is not a utility library and domain-specific logic is best left in userland. The default filters were provided for convenience but not for completeness.
2. As @blake-newman suggested, chaining an extra filter seems like a cleaner and smarter solution.

Although we are not merging this, we really appreciate your contribution!

