That's indeed problematic. I've decided to ditch event delegation all together in 423b54dfd41571fe45e7c46d465ad75665dc1b82. Since `v-on` auto unbinds listeners, the benefits of event delegation isn't that significant (and would actually result in slower handler invocation). That makes all handlers work the way they are expected to.
"That makes all handlers work the way they are expected to"
Meaning a handler that returns false translates to e.preventDefault?
Yes, just added a commit that returns the handler's return value from the wrapped handler.
Cool.
Is event delegation for v-repeat removed as well?
That is the area where delegation matters.
You could probably only implement delegation if a handler is nested under a v-repeat.
I've actually thought about it since long ago. Surprisingly, there's little hard evidence that shows any significant performance benefits of event delegation over simple listeners on a huge list. On a huge, huge list, adding the listeners would take more time and memory at boot time, but event delegation makes each event triggered much slower due to the delegation check overhead. It's a tradeoff. In `v-on`'s case, event delegation also adds a lot of complexity in trying to make handlers behave the way people expect them to be, so it no longer seem to be the optimal choice.
On a side note - angular refused to add event delegation to `ng-repeat` for similar reasons.

