This directive is an attempt to decouple as much of the DOM as possible from our ViewModel. With this directive you can set a control for the ViewModel scope with a specified key. Therefore instead of doing (using jQuery for quick example):

``` html
<div id="demo" v-on="click:fadeIn">
    <div class="sub-control">{{ message }}</div>
</div>
```

``` js
var demo = new Vue({
    el: '#demo',
    data: {
        message: 'Hello Vue.js!'
    },
    method: {
        fadeIn: {
            var el = $(this.$el),
                // what if our class name changes??
                subControl = $('.sub-control', el);

            subControl.fadeIn();
        }
    }
})
```

You can do this instead:

``` html
<div id="demo" v-on="click:fadeIn">
    <div v-control="sub-control">{{ message }}</div>
</div>
```

``` javascript
var demo = new Vue({
    el: '#demo',
    data: {
        message: 'Hello Vue.js!'
    },
    method: {
        fadeIn: {
            // does not care what class is, references controls key instead
            $(this.$controls['sub-control']).fadeIn();
        }
    }
})
```

Currently the directive will accept all letters, numbers, and `-_` characters as key values for the $controls object.

comments:
If you want to do it with DOM manipulation in your ViewModel, then I think this would be less intrusive than adding a `$controls` object to it ([JSFiddle](http://jsfiddle.net/obsoleter/ep9q6/)):

``` html
<div id="demo" v-on="click: fadeOut('.sub-control')">
    <div class="sub-control">{{ message }}</div>
</div>
```

``` javascript
var demo = new Vue({
    el: '#demo',
    data: {
        message: 'Hello Vue.js!'
    },
    methods: {
        fadeOut: function (sel) {
            var el = $(this.$el),
                subControl = $(sel, el);
            subControl.fadeOut();
        }
    }
})
```

Even better still, would be to keep DOM manipulation out of your ViewModel methods and in a directive ([JSFiddle](http://jsfiddle.net/obsoleter/ep9q6/2/)):

``` html
<div id="demo">
    <div v-on-parent-click="'fadeOut'">{{ message }}</div>
</div>
```

``` javascript
Vue.directive('on-parent-click', {
    update: function (value) {
        this.reset();
        this.handler = function (e) {
            $(this.el)[value]();
        }.bind(this);
        this.el.parentNode.addEventListener('click', this.handler);
    },
    unbind: function () {
        this.reset();
    },
    reset: function () {
        this.el.parentNode.removeEventListener('click', this.handler);
        this.handler = null;
    }
});

var demo = new Vue({
    el: '#demo',
    data: {
        message: 'Hello Vue.js!'
    }
})
```

I think the addition of a `v-control` directive would encourage some less than ideal patterns.
@obsoleter Excellent use of directives! Not that I am disagreeing with you on your point but what potentially bad patterns would arise with the v-control directive?
It's just that `v-control` does a great job making it easier to reference elements in the DOM from ViewModel methods.  That's a good thing if you want to encourage altering the DOM from the ViewModel, but when you do that it's all view manipulation and does not have to do with updating the model.  The purpose of the ViewModel is to link the view to the model and vice versa.  If the ViewModel has methods that only update the view, then the lines of responsibility between components starts blurring.  

It's the kind of thing that is a short term gain, but long term makes code difficult to debug and extend.  Just my two cents. :)
@obsoleter I really like your insight on the problem and I could see why long term this could have some negative effects. My underlying question for you or Evan would be what would be best practice for manipulating DOM elements? Custom directives? 

For example in one of my projects I am appending some DOM elements via AJAX and handlebars templates. Currently I am doing this straight in the ViewModel method like so:

``` javascript
submit: function() {
    if ($(this.$controls.textarea).val()) {
        var data = JSON.stringify(this.$data);

        app.ajax('post', URL.note.add, data, function(res) {
            var html = template['note-add'](res);
            $(this.$controls.list).prepend(html);
        });
    } else {
        $(this.$controls.textarea).addClass('error');
        return false;
    }
}
```

would it be better to simply reference the Vue model from a variable and grab its data from there? As an example:

``` javascript
var viewmodel = new Vue({...});

$('#foo').on('click', function(e) {
    if ($(this).val()) {
        var data = JSON.stringify(viewmodel.$data);

        app.ajax('post', URL.note.add, data, function(res) {
            var html = template['note-add'](res);
            $('#bar').prepend(html);
        });
    } else {
        $('#baz').addClass('error');
        return false;
    }
});
```
Custom directives would be my preference.  Vue lets you [register them globally](http://vuejs.org/api/global-methods.html#vue-directive-id-definition-) or add them as an [instantiation option](http://vuejs.org/api/instantiation-options.html#directives) when you create your ViewModel.
@BrandonPierce It seems like the issue is that you have an investment in Handlebars templates and you use jQuery to apply those templates.  If you rewrote your view (meaning, your html templates) using Vue's directives and some custom ones of your own, then it could look something like this:

``` html
<div id="main">
  <div v-if="uploadStatus" v-with="uploadStatus">
    <div v-text="statusCode"></div>
    <div v-text="statusMessage"></div>
  </div>
  <textarea v-model="textData" v-class="error: uploadError"></textarea>
  <button v-on="click: submit">Submit</button>
</div>
```

``` javascript
var vue = new Vue({
  el: '#main',
  data: {
   uploadError: false,
   uploadStatus: null
  },
  methods: {
    submit: function() {
      if (this.textData) {
        var data = JSON.stringify(this.$data);
        app.ajax('post', URL.note.add, data, function(res) {
          // assuming res has properties statusCode and statusMessage
          this.uploadStatus = res;
          this.uploadError = false;
        });
      } else {
        this.uploadStatus = null;
        this.uploadError = true;
        return false;
      }
    }
  }
});
```

[JSFiddle](http://jsfiddle.net/obsoleter/4u85q/)
@obsoleter is correct. The idiomatic approach in Vue is to write your code in a data-driven fashion. A ViewModel's `$data` not only hold data in the traditional Model sense, but also your View state. You should approach your app logic by thinking about pure states, instead of thinking directly about the DOM. When something needs to change, change the data first, and then define what that change should do to the DOM with directives.

So the best practice is what @obsoleter suggested: your ViewModel methods should try to be mostly about manipulating the state. This provides a separation of concerns and makes your logic easier to reason about and easier to test.
